                    <msContents n="2">
                        <!--increment n attribute for ms containing multiple ms items-->
                        <summary>A modern manuscript containing the <title xml:lang="san">Kauśīdyavīryotsāhanāvadāna</title> and the <title xml:lang="san">Snātāvadāna</title>. In Bendall's catalogue (1883)
                            this manuscript is described under two different classmarks, Add.1380
                                (<title xml:lang="san">Snātāvadāna</title>) and Add.1381 (<title xml:lang="san" type="alt">
                        <sic>Kauśighavīryotsāhanāvadāna</sic>
                     </title>), as if it were
                            two distinct manuscripts. However, many common features points to the
                            fact that they are two parts of one single manuscript (paper, folio dimensions,
                            layout and script are identical in the two). Moreover, in Add.1381 the
                            foliation ends with 11, while in Add.1380 it begins with 12 (and not
                            11, as stated in Bendall 1883: 80). These two <term xml:lang="san">avadāna</term>s belong to the cycle of king Aśoka and the monk
                            Upagupta, and are versified versions from the <title xml:lang="san" type="other">Ratnāvadānamālā</title>. In the edition by Takahata (1954), the
                            frame story of the <title xml:lang="san">Kauśīdyavīryotsāhanāvadāna</title> consists of only four stanzas
                            and is different from the one found in the present manuscript. His
                            edition is based mainly on a manuscript kept in the Kyōto University
                            Library, but in the critical apparatus he states that the longer version
                            in nine stanzas is witnessed in four other manuscripts used by him (it
                            is also present in a manuscript microfilmed by the Nepal-German Manuscripts Preservation Project
                            [NGMCP] with reel No. A 117-9, acc. No. NAK
                            3/596, and the title <title xml:lang="san" type="other">Avadānaratnamālā</title>). Parallel versions of the stories can be
                            found in other collections, like the <title xml:lang="san" type="other">Avadānaśataka</title> (II.3, <title xml:lang="san">Snātāvadāna</title>; I.3, <title xml:lang="san" type="other">Kuśīdāvadāna</title>). The title <sic>Kauśighavīryotsāhanāvadāna</sic> given in the
                            manuscript is wrong due to trivial scribal errors (<hi rend="italic">i</hi> instead of
                            <hi rend="italic">ī</hi>, and the common misreading of <hi rend="italic">gha</hi> for <hi rend="italic">dya</hi>, two <term xml:lang="san">akṣara</term>s very similar in Nepalese scripts).</summary>
                        
                        
